    <exercise id="fs-id2057574" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2055424">
      <para id="import-auto-id2381389"><title>Unreasonable Results</title></para>
<para id="eip-id2630197">Consider the circuit in <link target-id="fs-id1947335"/>, and suppose that the emfs are unknown and the currents are given to be <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>5</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>00 A</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:semantics></m:math>, <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mtext>.0 A</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{I rSub { size 8{2} } =3 "." 0" A"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, and <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>–2</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>00 A</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{I rSub { size 8{3} } "=-"2 "." "00"" A"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. (a) Could you find the emfs? (b) What is wrong with the assumptions?</para><figure id="fs-id1947335"><media id="fs-id2402951" alt="The diagram shows a complex circuit with two voltage sources E sub one and E sub two, and three resistive loads, wired in two loops and two junctions. Several points on the diagram are marked with letters a through h. The current in each branch is labeled separately.">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/Figure_22_03_09.jpg" width="250"/>
        </media>

      </figure></problem>

<solution id="fs-id3449782">
    <para id="import-auto-id3044256">(a) No, you would get inconsistent equations to solve.</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id1861422">(b) <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">≠</m:mo><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{I rSub { size 8{1} }  &lt;&gt; I rSub { size 8{2} } +I rSub { size 8{3} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. The assumed currents violate the junction rule.</para>
</solution>
